##I. Understanding Protocols
​A Protocol is a strict set of rules governing how data is exchanged. Even if a port is open, a connection will fail if the two devices do not speak the same protocol.
​##II. The TCP Three-Way Handshake
​Before any data is sent, TCP establishes a connection via a 3-step synchronization:
​SYN: Client asks to connect.
​SYN-ACK: Server acknowledges and asks to connect back.
​ACK: Connection established.
​##III. Hands-on Lab: Manual Handshakes
​I used telnet to manually initiate a TCP handshake with my local machine.
​Command: telnet localhost 8080
​Result: Connected to localhost. This confirms that the Python service on Port 8080 was successfully "Listening" and accepted the handshake.
​##IV. Troubleshooting: Port Conflicts & Escaping Sessions
​During the lab, I encountered a common networking error: OSError: [Errno 98] Address already in use.
​Lessons Learned:
​Port Exclusivity: Only one process can bind to a port at a time. If a previous session is still running (even in the background), a new service cannot start on that same port.
​The "Escape" Sequence: When trapped inside a telnet session, the standard exit command doesn't work. The correct escape sequence is Ctrl + ] followed by typing quit.
​Process Cleanup: Used pkill python3 to clear background processes and free up the port for a fresh session.
